@MeghanEBLin *hard not hate lol

@xMiriamST I encourage you to map yours to see where overloads originate. There are tipping point meltdowns where overstimulation over time can cause one minor thing to set off a meltdown. Again, for me it's usually sensory. Its not that I never have emotional ones, just rarely.

@xMiriamST I've journalled and napped mine and it's usually a sensory overload that's been recent. They can and do feel emotional because we are emotional creatures by nature. It's an emotional reaction to environmental triggers. My sensory overload always begins first.
@EChickentender Yes! Most people are incapable of doing just that and its dangerous to us and those around us

Usually it's flight. When a person follow me and keeps yelling I begin to meltdown. If the person physically tries to stop me or touches me I fight until left alone and then I go back into flight. My entire meltdown is a fight for survival.

That's because yelling effects my vestibular system and therefore my proprioception is thrown off to the point I do not know where I am in space. It's disorienting and my nervous system goes into fight or flight.
Prolonged yelling from anyone is a garenteed MD. Foot ball games. Nope. Boss yelling. Nope. Landlord going off. Nope. It's all the same to me. Head goes through wall. It's humiliation at it's worse.

Hunger, excitement, butterflies in your stomach can all tip over into a MD but they aren't emotionally linked in the traditional sense. My emotional outbursts and my meltdowns are remarkably different. It's like night and day.

I'm always hesitant to say emotional overload leads to MD because it implies that it can be counseled or therapized out of you as far as NT's and the medical community go. Very few are aware that it's not because your sad or depressed but it's because of an internal sensation.
Good stimuli can also cause meltdowns. A birthday party, a trip to the zoo, excitement because you got a promotion (sudden, but good, change).

Meltdowns are commonly defined as an intense emotional reaction to environmental factors. 

Which include: Sudden and impactful change, sensory overload, change to routine, change in a known environment, or just a pile up and tipping point of things over a course of months.
unless I was well prepared and certain no surprises awaited me.

Which are meltdowns that occur hours to days after the overstimulating event. When I was attending church I was melting down weekly before I knew what was going on. When I realized it was because of overstimulation I cut out all overstimulating events...

When my meltdowns happen it's primarily sensory. My journalling has shown to me that it's usually within 72 hours of an event that is overstimulating. On a rare occasion I will meltdown immediately but I tend to have delayed meltdowns.
@MeghanEBLin I try so hate to isolate but people have increasingly become aware of them. Sometimes I wonder if I know people that cause them on purpose.

All of mine are sensory related. I actually hold my emotions pretty well and there's a huge difference in the two.

So today when I pointed out the complete nonsense of the CDC BMI it was rather unnerving when someone told me to loose weight.

In highschool when my mother threatened to have me committed for anorexia was about 130 and a size 8. One lb overweight says BMI. My mom wouldn't let me eat toast bc it would make me fat. Did I mention that at this point in time I'm just 2 sizes larger than I was in highschool?

The problem was I was so brainwashed by medical facts and CDC BS I dismissed the fact that at my "normal" weight I was often viewed as having an eating disorder and told I needed rehab because I was too skinny. If I went over my high accepted weight I was told to lose.

None of this was taken into consideration. I walked all the time because walking for miles is a stim and Pokemon Go was an excellent way to mask this yet my muscle mass was also dismissed. It was the pursuit of health that lead me down the weight app road. BMI calculators are BS.
I also wore a 36 DDD bra. Yes, I was carrying around that much boob. It was one of my motivators because of the sensory issues and the backaches I kept up with the "diet" despite the consequences.
I was a size 12 but I also experienced almost daily edema. It was pretty severe. https://t.co/zOQZoZBYrB

If their was a food related function where I would eat high calorie foods or that I didn't know how many calories were in the food I'd cut my calories down for a day or two to compensate. Sometimes I didn't eat at all.
Given that Autistics especially those with an ADHD component often forget to eat or eat a limited amount of food do to sensory issues. I was often lightheaded and weak.

To this day I know a Sausage McMuffin w/Egg is 480 calories and a Whopper is 740. 

I assure you that peeling the breading off of Chicken Nuggets is seriously disordered eating. They are around 400 calories for a 10 pc btw.

In order to eat actual food and above my 1200 allotted calories a day I had to "earn" it with exercise. The easiest way to count calories was via prepackaged food such as TV dinners. Fast food was also a guaranteed calorie count.
(This was prior to knowing that I had health issues that caused me to gain. Meds, mainly gabapentin, packed on weight as well.)

I'm Autistic so you can just imagine how detailed and obsessive I got. No one should have to count calories for their same foods but I did. Spoiler alert. You can't heal from illnesses in only 1200 cals a day!

I used to be 200 lbs. We couldn't figure out why I was gaining weight and much of medical fluctuates on losing weight as a cure. 

Which it isn't. An illness caused me to gain.

I used MyFitnessPal which isn't much better than Noom. Anything that had calories had to be counted.

I've never tried it with vegan baco bits so idk how it would go) or whatever you would like to have in potato soup. I like to add cut up boiled or baked potatoes for substance and texture. Of course, skip the bacon bits if you prefer a meat free version.

From there you can add other ingredients based on your spoons (for new people spoons* equal energy units) like sauteed onions and celery (cook first then add water and potatoes to cut down on dishes), bacon bits (literally, pre cooked and crumbled bacon for salads...

If it calls for butter you can skip that if you'd prefer.

(When you figure out how much water to use you can even do this via the microwave.)

Low spoons food tip!

Add extra water to dry mashed potatoes mix to make potato soup. It makes a good sub in a pinch for soup and the packages are usually under $3 and as low as $1. Start with a couple of cups extra of water and add or boil down to the thickness you want.

Anyway, forgive me for having a bit of a down day of anti-Rittenhouse protesting. I'm not alone. Many Autistics experience this type of truth vs virtual truth dysphoria from life on a day to day basis. 

It's exhausting, isn't it?

Auts take life as it meets the eye. View it literally and deduce what happened. While NT's imagine what they want to believe as they want to see it. Seemingly an illusion they dreamed up because reality was too hard to bear. Perhaps it's self imposed pathological gaslighting?

but the Judge decided he wasn't guilty and convinced the jury via body language, subtle cues, and suggestions that what the nation clearly saw wasn't actually what happened at all. They all somehow decided that he was a victim when it was clear he was the antagonist.

to explain what happened and how they did it and the interaction and give rational details and all of them tell us that that's not what happened! Ya, that's how it is all the time for us. Like we saw in Rittenhouse's case. He clearly did it given all the evidence...

I feel guilty for not posting about Rittenhouse today but my mind is numb in that area at the moment.

This is what autistics go through every day in a neurotypical world. We will see NT's do something and can recall the literal steps they took and words they said...
